"1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1522":"1522","1489":"1489","about 1459":"about 1459","Abt 1465":"about 1465","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1541":"1541","1485":"1485","April 1470":"April 1470","about 1489":"about 1489","October 1491":"October 1491","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","All Hallows Parish, Lydd, Kent, England":"Lydd, Kent, England","Lydd, Kent, England":"Lydd, Kent, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Parre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian: from a short form of the personal name   Gasparro  , a variant of <i>Gaspare</i>, an equivalent of   Casper  .","Altered form of French   Perrault  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gasparro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Antonio, Costantino, Donato, Giuseppe, Leonardo, Mauro, Michelangelo, Nichola, Nicola.","Italian: from a variant of the personal name <i>Gaspare</i>, an equivalent of   Casper  ."]},{"name":"Parrillo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Carmine, Oreste, Pasquale, Vito, Antonio, Carlo, Enrico, Philomena, Rinaldo.","Italian:","from a pet form of the personal name   Parro  ."]},{"name":"Parrotta","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Nicola, Rocco, Umberto, Carlo, Dante, Domenic, Pasquale, Pietro.","Italian:","from a pet form of the personal name   Parro  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Agnes Parre was born in 1440, in Lydd, Kent, England. She married Thomas Bate about 1459, in Lydd, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. She died in October 1491, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1440–October 1491":"1440–oktoober 1491","1440–1489":"1440–1489","1461–Male":"1461–Surnud","1464–1485":"1464–1485","1465–1522":"1465–1522","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1470–1520":"1470–1520","1489–1541":"1489–1541","1440–1491":"1440–1491","October 1485":"oktoober 1485","October 1489":"oktoober 1489","1440":"1440","1461":"1461","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1522":"1522","1489":"1489","about 1459":"umbes 1459","Abt 1465":"umbes 1465","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1541":"1541","1485":"1485","April 1470"